		&nbsp;<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&id=5589"><img src="icon_profile.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Show Profile" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>
        
			&nbsp;<a href="JavaScript:openWindow('pop_mail.asp?id=5589')"><img src="icon_email.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Email Poster" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&REPLY_ID=18616&TOPIC_ID=1735&FORUM_ID=6&CAT_ID=1&Forum_Title=The+Great+Necro+Talks+2002&Topic_Title=Necro+%22Balancing%22&M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2"> 'Don't accept bland statements like this as though they are fact. They are supposition - nothing more.</P><P>The FACT however is that anyone casting dots on a mob is currently being shafted by VI. Checks are not made for the "stacking" of DD spells so why are they made for dots?'</P><P>Well, you do agree that a necro being able to chain-cast a DoT on a mob 15 times would be unbalancing, right?</P><P>...</P><P>So, the options are:<BR>1> Really long RCT on the DoT, preventing chain-casting.  Lower versions of spells overwriting higher versions.<BR>OR<BR>2> Knowing who cast a DoT on a mob, and only allowing 1 DoT per caster on the mob.  This requires extra data to be stored on the mob.<BR>OR<BR>3> Make DoTs suck unless you massively stack them.</P><P>From what I can tell, buff/debuffs work as follows:<BR>There are X slots on a PC/NPC.  Each slot has data for: # of an effect, and a countdown timer.</P><P>When a new effect lands, it is checked against all slots on the PC/NPC for stacking issues.</P><P>If any slot has an effect that prevents the spell from landing, it aborts & you get a 'does not stack' error message.</P><P>If not, it then looks for spells this spell overwrites.  It erases those effects.</P><P>Finally, it looks for the first empty slot on the mob.  If there are no empty slots, it erases the last slot, and writes itself there.</P><P>...</P><P>The real trick would be adding a "name" field to each buff/debuff slot, and transmitting the "name" along with the effect.  This would allow per-character non-stacking, but allow 2 necros to double dot a target.  They could even implement diminishing returns if pure stacking is unbalancing.</P><P>The above wasn't from reading EQ's code, I admit, but rather by paying attention to how it works in game, and what the developers say out of game, and ... holy shit ... 15 years of programming now.  Damn, I'm old.</P><P><BR> <a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height=15 width=15 border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
      </tr>

      <tr>
